<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">Biology. Rarely forming ripe seed in Norden.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">
Taxonomy. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">Chenopodium berlandieri</taxonomicName>
is widespread and morphologically variable in North America; several races have been described. Most of the plants collected in Norden (and all over Europe) have been referred to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Murr) A. Zobel" authorityName="(Murr) A. Zobel" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="berlandieri" subSpecies="zschackei">subsp. zschackei (Murr) A. Zobel</taxonomicName>
, which is also the most widespread race in North America and the only one reported from Canada. However, the variation has not been sufficiently studied in North America, and the use of infraspecific names for European casual material is premature. The relationship between 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="32" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">C. berlandieri</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="345" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hircinum">C. hircinum</taxonomicName>
(20) should be studied 
<bibCitation pageId="22" pageNumber="26">(Bassett &amp; Crompton 1982)</bibCitation>
; both are tetraploids with 2n=36.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="22" pageNumber="26" type="mainText">
Similar taxa. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="berlandieri">Chenopodium berlandieri</taxonomicName>
in fruit is easily recognized by the honeycomb-pitted seeds. - In the vegetative state sometimes taken for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="918" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">C. album</taxonomicName>
(15) or 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="1610" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="22" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="opulifolium">C. opulifolium</taxonomicName>
(21), but distinguished from both by the combination of yellowish stem, distinctly acuminate and relatively long leaf-blades with few teeth, and winged tepals. - Sometimes also similar to C. hircinum (20), but not stinking and with narrower, less distinctly 3-lobed leaf-blades.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
